******
[3]
Date: Tue 25 May 2010
Source: The Mainichi Daily News [abridged, edited]
<http://mdn.mainichi.jp/mdnnews/news/20100525p2g00m0dm049000c.html>


Farm minister Hirotaka Akamatsu apologized Tuesday [25 May 2010] over
the government's handling of the FMD outbreak in Miyazaki Prefecture,
backing away from his previous remarks that he has "nothing at all to
reflect on" over the issue.

"I feel deeply sorry that it has spread this much," Akamatsu told a
session of the House of Representatives committee on agriculture,
forestry and fisheries, with the outbreak likely to result in the
slaughtering of more than 30 000 cows and pigs.

Akamatsu was apparently forced to change his earlier stance, offering
a formal apology for the 1st time, as the situation appears to be
causing unprecedented damage to livestock.

While the agriculture, forestry and fisheries minister reiterated, "I
have done what was deemed necessary," he also expressed his intention
to examine the central government's handling of the issue after the
spread ceases.

"It is necessary to examine if the handling was really appropriate,"
Akamatsu said, responding to questions from main opposition Liberal
Democratic Party lawmaker Koichi Tani.

At a news conference before the committee session, Akamatsu said 73
percent of vaccinations, which the government began conducting last
week on livestock within a 10-km radius of infected farms in the
southwestern prefecture prior to slaughter, had been completed by
Monday [24 May 2010]. A further 30 000 livestock will be vaccinated,
and the task is expected to be basically completed later Tuesday, he
said. According to the Miyazaki prefectural government, 90 percent of
the vaccinations are likely to be completed by the end of Tuesday.

The farm minister also said the government will stick with its
decision Monday [24 May 2010] to slaughter 49 stud bulls in the
prefecture to prevent the spread of the disease, despite the desire
of local authorities to keep the animals alive.

The slaughter of the 49 stud bulls will leave only 5 to produce
Miyazaki Prefecture's prized beef, dealing a great blow to the local
livestock industry.

"It is stated in law that they must be terminated immediately once
designated as suspected cases," Akamatsu said.

During the lower house committee session, Senior Vice Minister of
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Masahiko Yamada said the spread
of the disease was caused by the infection of pigs, among which the
disease is highly contagious.

"Regrettably, we were not able to secure places to bury them,
allowing the disease to circulate," Yamada said.

LDP lawmaker Taku Eto urged the government to purchase land for the
burial of slaughtered cows and pigs in locations that will not be
used as farmland even 10 years from now, but the government did not
give a clear response.

The main opposition party plans to submit a no-confidence motion
against the farm minister as early as this week.

--
